post_text:
The Montgomery County Fatherhood Initiative, in partnership with the Montgomery County Office of Reentry, is excited to announce it is hosting a Back to School Supply Drive for students in need on Friday, Sept. 11, from 9 a.m. – 4 p.m., in The Job Center parking lot.

Students will receive a backpack full of various school supplies. It will also contain a folder with information on helping children become better students, as well as other relevant information for fathers such as employment and health resources. Backpacks are limited to one per child and a maximum of three per vehicle.

Participants must pre-register for a specific pick up time at https://www.signupgenius.com/go/5080848ada92ca2fe3-montgomery.

post_text:
Conundrums

One of the reasons why English is known for being difficult is because it’s full of contradictions. There are innumerable examples of conundrums such as:
• There is no ham in hamburger.
• Neither is there any apple nor pine in pineapple.
• If teachers taught, why didn’t preachers praught?
• If a vegetarian eats vegetables, what does a humanitarian eat?
• “Overlook” and “oversee” have opposite meanings, while “look” and “see” mean the same thing.

As native speakers, we rarely stop to think how illogical many of the things we say really are – we’re just used to them. Unless you’ve been brought up speaking English, how can you possibly begin to learn all these oddities? It’s little…

post_text:
A message from our English Department:

Studying English: It Could Be Worse

Babbel.com found that the most difficult world languages for native English speakers to learn are:
1. Mandarin Chinese (also the most widely spoken language in the world)
2. Arabic
3. Polish
4. Russian
5. Turkish
6. Danish
If you are fluent in English plus another language, or if you’re someone who takes to language easily, you might consider a career as a translator. It can be an exciting field, one that has you traveling to another country during your college years to build fluency, and ongoing opportunities to see the world throughout your career.
Next time: Why do non-native speakers find English so hard to learn?
Excerpted from Dylan Lyons in Babbel, May 22, 2017.
